      "value": "Cardiff Elementary is a very small elementary (K-6) district on the North Coast of San Diego County. About 106 of its students have an IEP, and 11 of them \u2014 roughly 10% \u2014 have an autism (ASD) eligibility. Around 64% of those autistic students spend most of the school day in a general-education classroom."
    },
    "what_this_means_for_parents": {
      "ai_disclaimer": "This summary was written by an AI model from the data points in this profile. The underlying numbers come from public California government sources, but the narrative is AI-written and may contain inaccuracies. Verify specific claims directly with the school district before making decisions.",
      "ai_generated": true,
      "ai_generated_at": "2026-05-17T21:27:27Z",
      "ai_model": "claude-opus (via Claude Code session)",
      "based_on_sources": [
        "cde_spedps",
        "ca_dashboard"
      ],
      "value": "About 64% of autistic students here are in a general-education classroom for most of the day, and none are reported in a fully separate setting. Among all students with disabilities, a broader group than autism alone, 72% are in general-education classrooms most of the day. On 2024-25 state tests, students overall scored above standard \u2014 54 points above in English and 40 above in math \u2014 while students with disabilities scored 14 points below in English and 23 below in math. No students were suspended in 2024-25 in either group, and chronic absenteeism was about 10% for students with disabilities and 7% for all students."
    }
  },
